  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 40.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Now when the sun was setting, all they that had any sick with divers diseases brought them unto him; and he laid his hands on every one of them, and healed them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The healing of the \"possessed\" in the synagogue that morning, followed by the cure of the fever of Simon's wife's mother, we know was rapidly noised abroad, and in great measure accoutered for the crowds who brought their sick to him in the evening. It was evidently in the life of Jesus a notable occasion, and many a sick tortured one had occasion to bless the Master's presence then. It was so memorable an occasion that all the three evangelists notice it; their reports are recorded in almost the same words. No doubt, in the early days of the preaching of the faith, this evening's work was constantly alluded to by the first teachers. The note of time, \"when the sun was setting,\" indicates that the moment in question had been waited for, for sunset ended the sabbath, and then those outside Capernaum and in its outlying suburbs were enabled to bring their sick and afflicted without infringing the strict sabbath rules. \"The twilight scene, of Jesus moving about with word and touch of healing among the sick and suffering, the raving and tortured crowd (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 4:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is one of the most striking in the Gospels, and St. Matthew quotes it as a fulfillment of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 53:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\" (Farrar). Luke 4:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
